From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0053/N] os_bsd.cpp: three CheriBSD/purecap mmap+path fixes

Three cohesive CheriBSD purecap fixes in os/bsd/os_bsd.cpp:

1. java_home strip: BSD-side path-stripping in `os::init_2_misc` assumes
   <home>/lib/<arch>/<vmtype>/libjvm.so (macOS style) and strips four
   path components. JDK 9+ modular layout for non-Apple has no <arch>
   dir; we end up with java_home = "/opt" instead of "/opt/jdk", which
   then fails at set_boot_path. Gate the extra strip on `__APPLE__`;
   non-Apple matches the Linux strip.

2. pd_commit_memory: the non-Apple non-OpenBSD path uses
   `mmap(MAP_FIXED, addr, R|W)` over a prior reservation to commit
   pages. On CheriBSD purecap, this fails with `errno=98` (the
   capability passed via `addr` doesn't permit the MAP_FIXED replace).
   The OpenBSD branch already works around this with mprotect; extend
   the OpenBSD branch to also cover `__CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__`.

3. anon_mmap: reservations use `PROT_NONE`. On CheriBSD purecap, the
   returned capability has no R/W/X permission bits, so a later
   mprotect(R|W) fails EACCES. Use `PROT_MAX(R|W|X) | PROT_NONE` so
   the capability records the maximum permissions it can ever have
   while leaving the page initially unmapped.

These three fixes together let the JVM reserve safepoint polling
pages, card tables, and metaspace regions (which all use the
reserve-then-commit pattern) on CheriBSD purecap.

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md (patch 0053)

--- a/src/hotspot/os/bsd/os_bsd.cpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/os/bsd/os_bsd.cpp
@@ -367,6 +367,7 @@
     }
     Arguments::set_dll_dir(buf);
 
+#ifdef __APPLE__
     if (pslash != NULL) {
       pslash = strrchr(buf, '/');
       if (pslash != NULL) {
@@ -377,6 +378,16 @@
         }
       }
     }
+#else
+    // FreeBSD/CheriBSD: modular JDK layout has no <arch> dir between lib
+    // and {server,client}/libjvm.so. Same as Linux. Strip only /lib.
+    if (pslash != NULL) {
+      pslash = strrchr(buf, '/');
+      if (pslash != NULL) {
+        *pslash = '\0';        // Get rid of /lib.
+      }
+    }
+#endif
     Arguments::set_java_home(buf);
     if (!set_boot_path('/', ':')) {
       vm_exit_during_initialization("Failed setting boot class path.", NULL);
@@ -1621,8 +1632,10 @@
 //       problem.
 bool os::pd_commit_memory(char* addr, size_t size, bool exec) {
   int prot = exec ? PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC : PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE;
-#if defined(__OpenBSD__)
-  // XXX: Work-around mmap/MAP_FIXED bug temporarily on OpenBSD
+#if defined(__OpenBSD__) || defined(__CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__)
+  // CheriBSD/purecap: MAP_FIXED mmap over a prior reservation with capability
+  // address fails (errno 98). mprotect on the existing capability works.
+  // Same approach as the OpenBSD MAP_FIXED workaround.
   Events::log_memprotect(NULL, "Protecting memory [" INTPTR_FORMAT "," INTPTR_FORMAT "] with protection modes %x", p2i(addr), p2i(addr+size), prot);
   if (::mprotect(addr, size, prot) == 0) {
     return true;
@@ -1766,7 +1779,17 @@
   // Map reserved/uncommitted pages PROT_NONE so we fail early if we
   // touch an uncommitted page. Otherwise, the read/write might
   // succeed if we have enough swap space to back the physical page.
+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+  // CheriBSD: PROT_NONE alone gives a capability with no R/W/X perms, so
+  // later mprotect(R|W) fails EACCES. PROT_MAX records the maximum
+  // permissions the capability can ever have; combined with PROT_NONE the
+  // page is initially unmapped but the cap retains the option to upgrade.
+  char* addr = (char*)::mmap(requested_addr, bytes,
+                             PROT_MAX(PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC) | PROT_NONE,
+                             flags, -1, 0);
+#else
   char* addr = (char*)::mmap(requested_addr, bytes, PROT_NONE, flags, -1, 0);
+#endif
 
   return addr == MAP_FAILED ? NULL : addr;
 }
